5. What are categories and stats for each main dish served and the method it is prepared?

There are six main type of dishes mentioned by respondents, almost 80 percent of respondents pick turkey as a main dish, with majority choosing baked turkey over roasted and other preparation methods. Second in popularity would be ham/pork and third one is Tofurkey.

thanksgiving %>%
  filter(celebrate == "Yes", main_dish != "Other (please specify)", main_dish != "I don't know", main_prep != "I don't know") %>%
  mutate(main_dish = as.factor(main_dish)) %>%
  mutate(dishes = fct_lump(main_dish, n = 6)) %>%
  mutate(main_prep = as.factor(main_prep)) %>%
  mutate(preparation = fct_lump(main_prep, n = 2)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(main_dish)) %>%
  count(dishes, preparation, sort = TRUE) %>%
  kbl() %>%
  kable_minimal(html_font = "Cambria", font_size = 14)

6. Create a data viz showing this in the most evident way. Provide your own legend and use themes.

thanksgiving %>%
  filter(celebrate == "Yes", main_dish != "I don't know", main_prep != "I don't know", main_dish != "Other (please specify)") %>%
  filter(!is.na(main_dish)) %>%
  mutate(main_dish = as.factor(main_dish)) %>%
  mutate(main_prep = as.factor(main_prep)) %>%
  count(main_dish, main_prep) %>%
  mutate(main_prep = fct_reorder(main_prep, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = main_dish, y = n / number_celebrate, fill = main_prep)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~ main_dish, scales = "free") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent_format()) +
  labs(x = "Main dishes",
       y = "Percent of people who celebrates",
       title = "Dishes served on Thanksgiving",
       fill = "Method of preparation") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Set3")

thanksgiving %>%
  filter(celebrate == "Yes") %>%
  filter(!is.na(family_income)) %>%
  count(family_income) %>%
  mutate(percent_cel = n / number_celebrate) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = "", y = percent_cel, fill = family_income)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", color = "white") +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +

        axis.text = element_blank(),

       fill = "Family income")

11. Present this information on a data viz

thanksgiving %>%
  select(id, starts_with("side"), starts_with("pie"), starts_with("dessert")) %>%
  select(-side15, -dessert12, -pie13) %>%
  gather(category, dish, -id) %>%
  filter(!is.na(dish),
         !dish %in% c("None", "Other (please specify)")) %>%
  mutate(category = str_replace_all(category, "[:digit:]", "")) %>%
  count(category, dish, sort = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(dish = fct_reorder(dish, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = dish, y = n /  number_celebrate, fill = category)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent_format()) +
  facet_wrap(~ category, scales = "free", ncol = 1) +
  labs(x = "Thanksgiving meals",
       y = "Percent of people who celebrates",
       title = "The most common pies, desserts and sides on Thanksgiving") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 6)) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Set3")

13. How do the servings differ by income?

Sides and pies appear on Thanksgiving table more often than desserts. All types of side and pies are more evenly distributed over the income range, whereas some desserts, like “Blondies” are more common in lower income families.

food %>%
  inner_join(thanksgiving, by = "id") %>%
  group_by(family_income) %>%
  count(family_income, dish, category) %>%
  filter(!is.na(family_income)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  kbl() %>%
  kable_minimal(html_font = "Cambria", font_size = 14) %>%
  scroll_box(height = "400px")

14. Present this information on a data viz

food %>%
  inner_join(thanksgiving, by = "id") %>%
  group_by(family_income) %>%
  mutate(families = n_distinct(id)) %>%
  count(family_income, families, dish, category) %>%
  filter(!is.na(family_income)) %>%
  filter(family_income != "Prefer not to answer") %>%
  mutate(percent1 = n / families) %>%
  filter(category == "pie") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = family_income, y = dish, size = percent1)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  scale_size_continuous(labels = percent_format()) +
  labs(x = "Family income",
       y = "Servings",
       title = "How do pies differ by income",
       size = "Popularity") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))
